<section class="card">
  <h2>Quebec Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Quebec spans multiple climate zones, from the warmer St. Lawrence Valley to much shorter
    seasons in central and northern regions. Frost timing, growing degree day accumulation,
    and effective planting windows vary widely depending on latitude and proximity to the river.
  </p>

  <h3>1) The St. Lawrence Valley runs warmer</h3>
  <p>
    Southern Quebec along the St. Lawrence River often benefits from longer frost-free
    windows and stronger seasonal heat accumulation compared to higher elevations
    and northern regions.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Longer fall windows</strong> improve odds for tomatoes and peppers finishing.</li>
    <li><strong>River moderation</strong> reduces some temperature extremes.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2) Northern and elevated areas shorten quickly</h3>
  <p>
    As you move north or gain elevation, frost-free days decline and total seasonal
    heat drops. Warm-season crops require careful variety selection and early starts.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re gardening in a tighter window, this overview of
    <a href="/guides/what-is-considered-a-short-growing-season/">
      what qualifies as a short growing season
    </a>
    can help frame realistic expectations.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Spring volatility is common</h3>
  <p>
    Late spring cold snaps are not unusual, particularly inland. Planting strictly by
    a fixed calendar date can expose transplants to unnecessary risk.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    To understand how frost timing and heat accumulation interact,
    see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">
      how frost dates and growing degree days work together
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Fall transitions can be decisive</h3>
  <p>
    In much of Quebec, late August and September bring steadily cooling nights.
    Once overnight temperatures drop, warm-season crops slow significantly,
    even before the first official frost.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re unsure whether a crop will finish,
    <a href="/guides/will-my-crop-mature-before-first-frost/">
      this explains how to estimate maturity before first frost
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Identify whether you're in the St. Lawrence corridor or a northern/elevated region.</li>
    <li>Match crop maturity to realistic remaining seasonal heat.</li>
    <li>Add buffer if you're inland, elevated, or in a frost-prone valley.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Quebec, regional location within the province often matters as much as
    the province itself when planning your garden.
  </p>
</section>